Pseudogymnoascus destructans Presence and Bat Morphometrics

Leah N. Crowley

2023-09-26

Wing from dead tri-colored bat (Perimyotis subflavus) shows points of orange-yellow fluorescence when exposed to UV light. Read more here.

What is Pd?

Pseudogymnoascus destructans (P. desctructans or Pd) is a psychrophilic fungus that is the causative agent for the disease white-nose syndrome (WNS), which is one of the most significant threats to many North American bat species. This fungus grows optimally between 12-15 degrees C and in areas of high humidity (over 85%), which happen to be characteristics similar to many North American bat hibernacula. In hibernation, as bats enter torpor, their body temperatures lower to match the ambient and fungus-supporting temperature of the hibernacula. When the fungus grows on the bat bodies, typically on wings and around their faces, it increases water loss from the bats bodies. Dehydrated, fungus-impacted bats arouse from torpor more frequently throughout hibernation to replenish water. However, increased arousals from torpor throughout the season cause bats to burn through their fat reserves too quickly. With no food outside to replenish these, WNS-impacted bats starve and rarely survive winter.

Hibernating little brown bats (Myotis lucifugus) with Pd growing on faces and wings. Read more here.

For this assignment, I used a data set from the Haase lab that includes data collected from 44 bats, specifically:

  • Bat age in years,

  • bat mass in grams, and

  • presence (1) or absence (2) of Pd on bat body

I was interested in looking at how bat age and mass may impact the probability that the fungus will be found on a bat. To do model and visualize this, I used a GLM with a binomial family and a logit link function, which is the default function for binomial data. As we discussed in class, the logit is the natural logarithm of the odds of occurrence; the odds are defined as the ratio of successes to failures.
